The '''Scottish crossbill''' ('''''Loxia scotica''''') is a small [[passerine]] [[bird]] in the [[finch]] family [[Fringillidae]]. It is [[endemic]] to the [[Caledonian Forest]]s of [[Scotland]], is one of only two land [[vertebrate]] species endemic to the [[United Kingdom]] (the other being [[red grouse]], ''Lagopus scotica'').

The genus name ''Loxia'' is from [[Ancient Greek]] ''loxos'', 'crosswise', and ''scotica'' is [[Latin]] for 'Scottish'.<ref name =job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A. | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location = London, United Kingdom | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages =[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n231 231], 351 }}</ref> The [[Scottish Gaelic]] name for a crossbill is ''Cam-ghob'', which means 'crooked beak'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/learn/wildlife/scottish-crossbill|title=Forestry and Land Scotland - Scottish Crossbill|website=forestryandland.gov.scot|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>

==History and current status==
The [[British Ornithologists Union]] first classed the Scottish crossbill as a separate and distinct species in 1980, but some ornithologists{{who|date=July 2024}} believed there was insufficient scientific research for its status. It was considered to be possibly a race of either the [[red crossbill]] or the [[parrot crossbill]], both of which also occur in the [[Caledonian Forest]].{{cn|date=July 2024}}

RSPB research showed that Scottish crossbills have quite distinct [[Bird flight|flight]] and excitement calls from other [[crossbill]]s&nbsp;&ndash; some{{who|date=July 2024}} even stated they have "[[Scottish English|Scottish accents]]".{{cn|date=July 2024}}

Research in Scotland has shown that red, parrot and Scottish crossbills are reproductively isolated, and the diagnostic calls and bill dimensions have not been lost. They are therefore good species.<ref name= Summers >{{cite journal| last= Summers | first= R. W. |author2=Dawson, R. J. |author3=Phillips, R. E.| year= 2007| title= Assortative mating and patterns of inheritance indicate that the three crossbill taxa in Scotland are species| journal= Journal of Avian Biology | volume=38 | issue= 2| pages= 153–162 | doi =10.1111/j.0908-8857.2007.03798.x }}</ref>

The population is thought to be approximately 20,000 birds.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=8877 |title=Scottish Crossbill (Loxia scotica) - BirdLife species factsheet |access-date=2014-11-06 |archive-date=2014-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107024759/http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=8877 }}</ref> It nests in [[pine]]s or other [[conifer]]s, laying 2-5 [[egg]]s.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

The Scottish crossbill breeds in the native [[Scots pine]] (''Pinus sylvestris''), Caledonian forests of the [[Scottish Highlands]], but often also in [[forestry]] [[plantation]]s of [[Introduced species|exotic]] [[conifer]]s, notably [[Larch]] (''Larix decidua'' and ''L. kaempferi'') and [[Lodgepole pine]] (''Pinus contorta'').{{cn|date=July 2024}}

This species of crossbill is resident, and is not known to [[bird migration|migrate]]. It will form [[Flock (birds)|flocks]] outside the breeding season, often mixed with other crossbills.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

The [[crossbills]] are characterised by the mandibles crossing at their tips, which gives the group its [[English language|English]] name. They are specialist feeders on [[conifer cone]]s, and the unusual bill shape is an adaptation to assist the extraction of the seeds from the cone. The Scottish crossbill appears to be a specialist feeder on the cones of pines (Scots pine and Lodgepole pine) and larch.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

Adult males tend to be red or orange in colour, and females green or yellow, but there is much variation.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

The Scottish crossbill is extremely difficult to separate from the red and parrot, and [[Feather|plumage]] distinctions are negligible. The head and bill size is intermediate between and overlapping extensively with the other two, and extreme care is needed to identify this species. The metallic ''jip'' [[Bird call|call]] is probably the best indicator, but even this needs to be recorded and analysed on a [[Spectrogram|sonogram]] to confirm the identity.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

===Bill structure===

According to a lengthy scientific study by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] (RSPB), 'Celtic' crossbills differ in bill size from other crossbill species found in [[Great Britain]], and they have also been found to have a distinct Scottish accent or call, thought{{by whom|date=July 2024}} to be the method used by the birds to make sure that, especially given the physical similarities with other crossbills, they only attract and pair with potential mates of the same species.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

The most important evidence to come from the RSPB's long term study in the Highlands focused on discovering if the birds mate with those with a similar bill size and call, and whether young Scottish crossbills inherit their bill sizes from their parents.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

Results showed that, of over 40 pairs of different types{{clarify|date=July 2024}} of crossbills caught, almost all matched closely for bill size and calls, so the different types of crossbills were behaving as distinct species.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

===Calls===

The calls can be distinguished by [[spectrogram|sonograms]]. This provides the basis for a method to survey crossbills and, for the first time, gain a clear picture of their numbers and distribution in Scotland and help in any [[conservation movement|conservation]] programmes for the race.{{cn|date=July 2024}}

===Conservation===
The first survey of Scottish crossbills was in 2008.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Summers |first1=Ron W. |last2=Buckland |first2=Stephen T. |date=June 2011 |title=A first survey of the global population size and distribution of the Scottish Crossbill Loxia scotica |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0959270909990323/type/journal_article |journal=Bird Conservation International |language=en |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=186–198 |doi=10.1017/S0959270909990323 |issn=0959-2709|hdl=10023/1957 |hdl-access=free }}</ref>

Despite lacking data for population trends, [[British Birds (magazine)|British Birds]] places the crossbill on their Amber list for conservation concern on the basis of it being an endemic species and therefore of 'international importance'.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eaton|first=Mark|date=December 2015|title=Birds of Conservation Concern 4: the population status of birds in the UK, Channel Islands and Isle of Man|url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/BoCC4.pdf|journal=British Birds|volume=108|pages=708–746}}</ref> A 2017 report by the [[British Trust for Ornithology]] identified the crossbill as being at high risk of extinction.<ref>Hayhow, DB et al. [https://www.bto.org/sites/default/files/publications/state-of-uk-birds-_2017.pdf "The state of the UK's birds 2017"] (PDF) Sandy, Bedfordshire: The RSPB, BTO, WWT, DAERA, JNCC, NE and NRW.</ref>

Breeding populations exist at Corrimony Nature Reserve,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Corrimony Nature Reserve, Highland, Scotland|url=https://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves-and-events/reserves-a-z/corrimony/|access-date=2020-11-24|website=The RSPB|language=en-GB}}</ref> and Loch Garten Nature Reserve, one of the United Kingdom's most protected nature sites.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Loch Garten Nature Reserve, Abernethy, Scotland|url=https://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves-and-events/reserves-a-z/loch-garten/|access-date=2020-11-24|website=The RSPB|language=en-GB}}</ref>

One of the main threats to the crossbill's habitat is wood and pulp plantations, plus underplanting conifers and grazing pressure.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=BirdLife International |date=1 October 2016 |title=Loxia scotica, Scottish Crossbill |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22720641/88690876#conservation-actions |journal=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22720641A88690876.en |issn=2307-8235 |access-date=31 July 2023|doi-access=free }}</ref>

The main active conservation initiative is the implementation of the EU Biodiversity Action Plan, which seeks to protect the numerous species of birds throughout the EU.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=1996-10-01 |title=Birds in Europe: their conservation status  |journal=Choice Reviews Online |language=en |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=34–0930b–34-0930b |doi=10.5860/CHOICE.34-0930b |doi-broken-date=1 July 2025 |issn=0009-4978}}</ref> Further studies are needed to establish the species of trees Scottish crossbills are best adapted to, as well as population trends.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Summers |first1=Ron W. |last2=Buckland |first2=Stephen T. |date=2010-01-11 |title=A first survey of the global population size and distribution of the Scottish Crossbill Loxia scotica |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0959270909990323/type/journal_article |journal=Bird Conservation International |language=en |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=186–198 |doi=10.1017/S0959270909990323 |issn=0959-2709|hdl=10023/1957 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> It has also been suggested to prevent any further loss of habitat, and further restrict [[red deer]] grazing.<ref name=":0" />

